Introduction¶

In this project, I will use machine learning models to determine if someone is a good credit card candidate or not.

Before we begin, lets understand how credit cards work and the business decisions a Credit Card company (CC) needs to make. Credit cards allow the cardholder to spend money on credit, essentially borrowing money they may not have immediately but can pay back over time. Cardholders benefit from the obvious convenience of credit cards and often also enjoy other cash back or travel-related rewards the card company offers. The cardholder, on the other hand, is expected to pay the CC company the outstanding balance back.

The CC makes money by a) charging an interest on any outstanding / unpaid balance past the first payment period, b) levying late fees when the cardholder fails to make the minimum payment by the due date and c) through interchange fees paid by merchants on every transaction. Like with any loan, theres risk that the borrower is unable to pay the CC back and they are delinquent, ie., late in their payment or even in default, ie., unlikely to pay the outstanding back. While some delinquency is economically beneficial to the CC (due to interest charges and late fees), too much of it is not.

So, a CC has to understand that risk and reward tradeoff right upfront and only approve applicants / borrowers who meet certain criteria and where the CC can price for the risk. To do so, a CC typical develops a Credit Risk model and a Valuation model and then use them in conjunction to establish decision criteria for approval. The Credit Risk Model attempts to discriminate between good and bad applicants, where a bad applicant is likely to default and a good one is not. Valuation Models predict the expected lifetime value (in terms of income or profits) a borrower will generate for the CC In this exercise, well only concern ourselves with the former, ie., a Credit Risk model.

I got my data from a kaggle dataset which consists of two different datasets, as described below: a) Application Data: A file with one record per applicant with various features about the applicant b) Credit Data: A file with one record per applicant (borrower) per month (pay period) indicating whether the cardholder / borrower had a balance in that month and whether or how delinquent they were

I am framing this as a binary classifcation problem to discriminate between good applicants vs. bad applicants purely based on their likelihood to repay / not default. As noted previously, the valuation part of the equation will be ignored.

I will evaluate different machine learning models to find one that does the best job of discriminating between the bads and the goods.

Let's now jump into the data.

def create_cat_graphs(df):
    cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
    for col in cols:
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
        df[col].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
        plt.title(f'Bar plot for {col}')
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()
        
create_cat_graphs(application_clean)

Dummify and Scale Explanatory Variables¶

Why do we dummify and scale variables? To begin with, the variables that get dummified are categorical variables, that are either nominal (no order) or ordinal (have an order). For example, the variable NAME_INCOME_TYPE is an ordinal variable because it's used to describe educational status. The variable OCCUPATION_TYPE can be interpreted as a nominal variable.

Dummification takes all unique observations within a categorical variable and splits them up into their own variable, which then gets denoted with binary (1/0) notation. For a variable with k different observations, k-1 dummy variables will be created. For example, if we had a variable called "Color", with the observations being "Red", "Green", "Blue", and "Yellow", this variable would be dummy coded by created variables within the dataframe called "Color_Red", "Color_Green", and "Color_Blue". If the original color was Red, Color_Red would be marked as 1, with the other two marked as 0, and this would be the case for Green and Blue as well. However, if every entry for the newly created dummy variables is 0, that means the color variable value was Yellow.

The variables that get scaled are continuous explanatory variables. These do not include binary variables because those are denoted by either 1 or 0. Variables such as income, age, years employed will get scaled and we do this so that they can be compared to their means and standard deviations. The scaler we will use will return the z-score of each variable, and we will be able to understand how each entry is scaled relative to others.

This is now the final dataset that we will use for our models and to split the data into training and testing. Without further ado, let's get straight into it.

Feature Selection and Train/Test Split¶

In machine learning, we use a train/test split to evaluate the performance of a model. It's a standard practice to use at least 70% of data for training and the remaining data for testing. The training data is used to fit the model, and we use the testing data for predictions on new, unseen data. I will be using a 70/30 training/testing split. The purpose of doing this is to avoid overfitting, where we have a model that performs very well on given data but poorly on new data. We will stratify on our outcome variable, GOOD_BAD.

For all our models, the following process will be followed:

a) create predictions and illustrate through a classification table

b) oversampling data and creating new predictions, illustrating with a classification table

c) k-fold cross validation (using the original model fit)

d) hyperparameter tuning (for models that require)

e) k-fold cross validation on hyperparameter tuned models (for models that got tuned)

Metric Evaluation¶

There are several ways to evaluate the performance of a classification model. Some common metrics include: ROC_AUC, Accuracy and Balanced Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1 Score.

In our case, due to significant class imbalance, simple measures like accuracy will not work. But measures like Precision, Recall and F1 will.

A high recall (for bads) means that the model is able to correctly identifying most the bads in the population.

A high precision (for bads) means that when the model thinks that something is bad, it very likely is.

We want both. And a F1 Score, which is the harmonic mean of Recall and Precision, is a good way to measure this. For this reason, Ive chosen to use the F1 Score as the primary metrics to evaluate model performance.

The models I've chosen to fit are Logistic Regression, Quadratic Discriminant Analysis, XGBoost, and Random Forest, and I will provide explanations for them in their respective sections.

Logistic Regression Model¶

Logistic Regression models aim to predict the probability that an instance belongs to a certain class. In our class, that will be predicting, based on the predictor variables that we defined above, if a candidate is good (0) or bad (1).

Oversampling Data¶

Why is data oversampled? In cases similar to what we have, we want to have equal representation of class instances so that a model can better predict the lesser-represented instances. In all the models we fit, we are concerned with how well the model can predict bads, and that is the underrepresented class instance.

In Python, SMOTENC is a commonly used library used to oversample data. It's an acronym for Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique for Nominal and Continuous, and in our case, we put all the nominal variables (which are integers because of dummy coded) into the formula so that the entire dataset can be oversampled with respect to those variables.

K-Fold Cross Validation¶

The purpose of k-fold cross validation is to create "k" different folds within a given dataset, of which, k-1 folds are used for training data, and the remaining 1 fold is used for testing data. This process is repeated k times. It doesn't make the data dependent on any train/test split, which allows the model to be more robust.

Because the original dataset is imbalanced, I will be using a pipeline which overasamples the data while holding out data for training/testing folds. I will be doing this for all of my models.

In [109]:
from imblearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold, cross_validate
logistic_steps = [('over', SMOTENC(categorical_features = cat_cols)), ('model', logistic_model)]
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=logistic_steps)
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
scoring = ["accuracy", "roc_auc", "precision", "recall", "f1_weighted"]
scores = cross_validate(pipeline, x_train, y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, return_train_score = True)
print(scores)

XGBoost Model¶

Before we explain what exactly an XGBoost model is, we must understand how gradient boosted models work. And that is by building on previous models formed within the gradient boosting algorithm to accurately predict the outcome variable. XGBoost is a very commonly used gradient boosted method used due to its scalability and process speed.

In [120]:

Random Forest Model¶

Random Forest models randomly select subsets of data from the given dataset and makes a decision tree for each subset. Each decision tree, based on the data that it was derived from, will make a decision on the outcome variable. The random forest as a whole will then make a decision on the outcome variable based on the decisions of the decision trees that were created within the model.

Model Selection¶

It is time to compare the models! As stated earlier, the benchmark score that I will be using as a comparison metric is f1 score because it's a good harmonic mean of precision and recall, and because this overall data is imbalanced, we will get the best vision on how the data performed by looking at f1 score.

In [149]:

From the plot above, we can see that the models with the best f1 scores after cross validation are the XGBoost model and Random Forest. But this plot is only after cross validating on the original fit data, because there were no hyperparameters to tune for either logistic regression or QDA.

Just for good measure, we will make a plot of the f1 scores of XGBoost and Random Forest after cross validating the hyperparameter-tuned models. And we will compare these values to the cross-validated f1 values of the logistic regression and QDA to ensure that XGBoost and Random Forest are still the two best performing models.

Conclusion and Findings¶

Just like how we did with the training data, let's make a plot of the f1 scores to see which model performed better.

In [156]:
models = ['XGBoost', 'Random Forest']
f1_cv_scores = [0.817, 0.8334]
plt.bar(models, f1_cv_scores, color = "orange")
plt.xlabel("Models")
plt.ylabel("F1 Scores")
plt.title("F1 Scores for Testing Data")
plt.show()

From f1 score, we can see that random forest was the best performing model. We have a lot of metrics in the tables, but the final metric I want to compute is ROC-AUC. ROC-AUC calculates a model's ability to distinguish classes in a binary classification problem by comparing the true positive rate to the false positive rate.

In [157]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
xgb_best_roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_test_best_xgb)
print("XGB Final test ROC-AUC:", xgb_best_roc)
rf_best_roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_test_best_rf)
print("Random Forest Final test ROC-AUC:", rf_best_roc)

XGB Final test ROC-AUC: 0.7129497756379729
Random Forest Final test ROC-AUC: 0.747914630985989

A higher ROC-AUC score is better, so by looking at both f1 score and ROC-AUC, the random forest model is the best performing model. I am not too surprised by this result given how the model was performing before any cross-validation or oversampling happened, and this can be attributed to the robustness of the model. With a combination of both continuous and dummified variables that were used, it makes sense that decision-tree based models would perform better than non decision-tree based models, which is also why the XGBoost model performed well with data to begin with. The difference in performance with the training and testing data is expected because the new data wasn't trained on.

It's a very good sign that both the random forest and XGBoost models were able to predict on bad candidates. This is something that companies need to be watchful for when deciding who to give credit cards to. The more "bad" candidates you're able to catch, the more you're able to protect your risk as a company.

It's also worth noting that the criteria that I selected for my GOOD_BAD variable is much simpler than what is actually used in real-life scenarios. But this project was still a fun one that aligned with my interests in risk and decision making, and might be one that I continue building upon with unsupervised learning techniques as I progress as a data scientist.
